This is my 3rd version of printable LM8UU bushings.
Prusa suggested to me that putting some spring/give in them could be a good idea, so I gave it a go.
They're more than strong enough to handle the forces they get subjected to, and as an added bonus they're far less likely to crack your X-ends when you insert them since they'll happily compress a little.
I replaced a set of my original bushings with these, they're still wearing in but seem to work great so far. It certainly solved the chatter problem I had!
PLEASE NOTE: ABS is not a suitable material for bushings. It's too soft so it has lots of friction and wears quickly. These printed in ABS would be a novelty only, not a useful part.
PLA works well, as will any other hard plastics.

Open the scad file, enter values from your slicer particularly extrusion width.
render, slice and print!
You should print at least 4 at a time if not more, especially if you have a high perimeter feedrate (this model is 100% perimeters, no infill at all!).
cooling will be required.
Once printed, you may need to run them up and down your threaded rod a little so they're not so stiff.
Use suitable grease.

description.text:
This is a quick development of a neck strap balancer for the Devo 7E.
I am sure people can use it for other radios.

To print(I print with Repetier-Host):
1.Rotate the part to lay it flat (-90deg X-axis)

  1. Create a copy of the part.
  2. Mirror the copy part.

Note:

  1. The mounting hole is along the X-axis. Thats how it was my devo 7E and I decided to keep it that way. Please feel free to change it.
  2. You will need a small piece of steel wire(~1.5mm dia) , some CA glue and a M3x10mm screw and nut to assemble.
  3. You should be able to snap the part out of the radio after removing the M3 screw.

Key Features:

  1. The concept of using metals or other materials to augment the process of FDM 3d printing interests me. Hence this design.
  2. Prints really quick(20min) without support.
  3. The direction of the layers ensures that the part has maximum functional strength.

  3. If the wire groove is not a perfect fit, use a hot soldering iron to nudge the wire piece into the grooves.

description.text:
Very often once you have the entire power/drive train calculated and ironed out for max efficiency, you do not get the perfectly sized folding prop.

Here I try to explore the concept of having a kit that transforms any prop to a folding prop.

As a starting point i present only the very popular 10x4.5" prop.
This is to go with a A2212/1000kv motor onto a Blunt-Versa wing. (in my case!!)

The print layer direction has been very specifically chosen to optimize on print strength.
Hence the supports are also included to work perfectly. Do not use auto-generated supports for this print.
I include a few Gcode files for use as examples to setup the built plate in your slicer of choice. This is important.

This prints fine in PLA and I have tested the setup on a 3S lipo with 700gms thrust. The blades are stable and vibration free. Probably ABS is better (only after thorough acetone treatment!!) But most people have their printers setup to print PLA reliably so I chose to use PLA.

As always, I would thank the community to have taught me so much. And ask anyone/everyone to take forward my work and improve it. I include source files in the post.
Hopefully some other very popular props.
Maybe someone does some more tests and improves the design.
I would love something more 'universal'.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3 Rework

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

NOTE/WARNING: the part spins at very high speeds so it is dangerous. Take necessary precaution. PLEASE!.

  1. Make sure your printer is very well tuned and you get generally strong parts.
  2. You can bump up the print temperature a couple of degrees to get much better inter layer adhesion.
  3. If your print in ABS, do make sure you do a through acetone treatment to fuse layers.
  4. Never miss out on balancing your props before putting on a motor.
  5. Make sure you have a vibration free motor and mount.
  6. Wear eye protection when running tests.

Assembly
  1. Remove supports and sand off the support marks.
  2. Carefully drill the M3 and M5 holes making sure you do not get a layer separation.
  3. Run thin CA glue on the layers (PLA) to make the parts stronger.
  4. Assemble using appropriately sized M3 screws and lock-nuts. (or thread lock)
  5. Place the assembly and the prop on a M5 rod/screw/bolt and mark the propeller for cut marks using a sharpie. The target is to keep the final dia of the folding-prop to be same as the original fixed-prop.
  6. Cut the original prop using a hacksaw. (careful with a dremel / highspeed tool. It will deform the plastic prop shape)
  7. Sand the ends of the blade so that it gets into the blade-holders. check fit.
  8. fix the blades to the blade-holder with epoxy. (use a slower one for better strength and penetration)

TIP: all you have to make sure is that the propeller is symmetric on both the blades.

description.text:
I design this raspberry pi retro handheld gaming console from scratch because I cannot find the specific ready-made case for all my needed parts for my personal retropie console project. The printed case came out good and fit every parts just nicely. And I'm really enjoying playing all those retro games from snes and gameboy advance. Really satisfied with the final product.

Design and drawing using solidworks.

As for reference, the parts that I use in this built is as follows:

  1. Raspberry Pi 2 Model B
  2. 5-inch HDMI LCD display with hdmi link connector (from aliexpress)
  3. Hacked SNES USB gamepad (from ebay)
  4. USB Li-ion charging circuit board (from dx.com)
  5. 2000mah 3.7v li-ion battery (taken from my broken china tab)
  6. mini 2.5w amplifier board
  7. 2x 4ohm mini speaker
  8. power switch
  9. 2 extra tactile switch for left/right shoulder button
  10. mini wifi dongle (for roms transfer)
  11. some wires and screws

--about the hdmi lcd display

--about the snes gamepad
To simplify my build (also to save time) I just dismantle the usb gamepad, reuse all the pcb, the silicone switch, the buttons and d-pad itself. As for the usb connection, I soldered directly the wires from the pcb to the usb pad on Rasp-Pi. All internally connected. It works just great but future plan will use analog stick for more easy control.

That’s right! It’s finally time for Wall-E. This is a semi-functional Wall-E Robot that I created in Tinkercad, printed out on my Robo3D and painted by my wife using spray painting, airbrush painting and brush painting techniques.

I have links to the files for Wall-E listed below. Please note that there are two versions of some files. These are basically for the electronic and non electronic versions. The only two files with multiple versions are the neck files and the leg bracket files. These files have “Non Electric” in the file name so they’re easy to spot.

In the electronic version of Wall-E there are 43 individual files, 84 main parts, 72 treads, and 144 pins needed. So that's a total of 300 individual parts that need to be printed.

This is a list of the electronics components that I used. However, be aware that the DC motors I chose to drive Wall-E DO NOT work. They don’t have enough torque to drive him. So if you want to try to make this robot work, you’ll either need to redesign the legs/wheel mounts, or you’ll need to find a really high torque motor that is in a micro servo casing. The mounts I have built in fit micro servos specifically and it would be difficult to fit any other sized motors here.

Sub Micro Servo (Neck/Head):
https://www.adafruit.com/products/2201
DC Motors in a Micro Servo Body (Drive Motors):
https://www.adafruit.com/products/2941

There were a few other components I used like an Arduino Uno to control the whole thing, a bluetooth chip to control it with my phone, and a speaker to have him make noises. But these are not specifically fitted in here, so as long as you can fit it in the body, you’ll be good. So you can use your favorite components for this.

I also used #8 ½ inch screws and nuts to put him together and parts are fitted for these screws specifically. You’ll need roughly 30 screws for this. Most of the time the screws will screw right into the plastic and you won’t need the nuts, but most places have the ability to insert nuts if needed. Up to you.

Also some of the STLs will need to be printed more than once to complete Wall-E so I’ll put the quantity needed in the STL file name.

I will be creating some diagrams to show how Wall-E is assembled shortly. So if you’re looking to build this for yourself, check back in a few days for those.

I really hope you enjoyed this project. Let me know what you thought. Happy printing. :)

The Non Electronic files are added now. It turns out I only needed to change the neck piece out. So instead of printing all the pieces with "neck" starting them. You can just download the "neck non electronic" file and that'll take care of the whole neck. The other part I was considering changing was the motor mounts for the legs but I would have to redesign that whole section so the parts will work without motors, there will just be a small gap underneath him.

comments.text: Hi! We want to develop microfluidic chips for Lab-on-a-Chip appllications and this test was a mock-up to see if we can do this with our B9Creator and with the materials we can find. We covered these slides with a glass slide with corresponding holes or with other 3D printed slides (more easy and efficient). The idea is to drop a drop of juice from a farm product and by capillary effect the juice is sucked in the thin channels and races to the breathe holes available. This mock-up test only has one breathe hole but the real chip will have many, with an intricate network of channels leading the juice to many small chambers htat will have many ways to detect different substances in the juice and, at the end, give the farmer, the store or the consummer a complete list of what's contained in the product. The farmer can send this information to an Open Data Base witch will certify (or not) his product. With the certification, the small local producer can finally be able to compete with the Big Agros on the local market and actually beat them at their own game. As Consummers, we would prefer having access to fresh and delicious local products but some lows and ''safety'' procedures patented and monopolized by Porcorations come in-between us and the local producers, and we know how effective they are ;) to pinpoint problems when they throw tons of products in case they could be contaminated. We want to develop an Open Source, cheap, user friendly device, that speaks to a smart phone, tablet or laptop, that can be implemented at all levels of the chain from farm to home. With a drop of juice at each checkpoint, problems are easy to pinpoint and consummers would be aware of what they're eating they can compare Agro products with local products... Lab-on-a-chip technology is now wide spread an cheap enough and if we can 3D print tiny disposable or reusable microfluidic chips we can bring this aparatus to market for about 50$ a piece. Interested? You can join our efforts!

The fractalizator is a monster object creator.

This is an OpenSCAD script that simply takes a .STL model and iteratively adds it to itself following a radial pattern. This is done recursively so that in the end the resulting object appears like a fractal. You can use any .STL file to create your 'fractalizations'.

Try to use simple objects and low ievel numbers at first to achieve some expertise, as complex model fractalizations could take a lot of time to be rendered and produce monster STL files. Anyway this is just for that, for producing MONSTER objects. I'm crazy I'm crazy I know...

Instructions included in the code, so I don't repeat here.
Download and install OpenSCAD if you don't have it. Download the files to a folder of you choice and open the .scad script. Press F5 for a quick view or F6 for a full render and STL creation.

Included are a couple example fractalizations. One is a fractalization of a single cilynder, and the other is a monster fractalization of my Marvin model here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:971828

Happy fractalizations!!

description.text:
The drag chain I have on my ox cnc is slightly arching, so I made this bracket to help keeping it straight. The bracket is made to fit on a vslot 2040 profile, and my drag chain is 50 mm wide.

I made two versions. One is made to sit center on a 2040. It is held in place with T-nuts in the profile, and will therefore also fit other profiles than 2040. After I printed the one in the photo, I went back and counter sunk the screw wholes.

But as I did not mount the drag chain so that it is centered on the vslot profile, I made a second version that is equally offset (I mounted the chain directly in one of the wholes that are in it). For this version I dropped the idea with the t nut, and instead the bracket is made to grab around the vslot. Therefore this bracket will only fit a 2040 profile. I kept the wholes for the screws just in case, but the bracket sits quite snug, so I will need them.

description.text:
My previous shot at this[1] didn't manage to blow too much air onto the nozzle. Some people were even beginning to try dangerous things to get it to blow harder, like blocking the air path through the radiator fins.

A better solution is, of course, a beefier fan! The standard Mk7 fan is rather wimpy, but you can get 4mm fans which will blow much harder (see the second picture for a comparison). Since there's more flow all around, we can even divert a larger portion of it towards the nozzle, so I changed the duct to do just that.

With this setup, I get quite a strong air flow around the nozzle.

[1] http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16392

1) (optional) Use a 3mm tap to thread the top holes
2) disassemble the Mk7 extruder
3) re-assemble using this duct instead of the fan, using the long bolts that hold the original fan in the duct's bottom holes.
4) fasten the fan to the duct using two M3x16 bolts through the fan's top holes.
5) print!

make sure to get rid of excess glue

Step 3: Assemble the back Step 3: Assemble the back Step 4: Make the tiles

Slide one of the square tiles shaped as an L on the base you previously made. The etched edge of the tile should rest right under the lip you've made.

Stick the pieces with the corners cut off (middle pieces) with glue for all of the 8 tiles.

Step 4: Make the tiles Step 4: Make the tiles Step 4: Make the tiles Step 5: Oil and Sand pieces

Take the half assembled tiles and give it a quick sand . Also add a tad of danish oil (if you have some) to prevent catching of the pieces. If you're still having problems, round out the corners.

Step 5: Oil and Sand pieces Step 5: Oil and Sand pieces Step 6: add your design

Whether you're painting a design or just placing an image on the tiles, this is the time to do so. We used acrylic paint, but if you have pieces of masking tape to cut, you could spray paint them.

Step 6: add your design Step 6: add your design Step 6: add your design Step 7: Final assembly

We've provided two ways to finish off the puzzle:

1: Glue all the tops of the tiles together and put them into the puzzle. Glue the skinny "L" shaped piece with the final square into the frame. This way, all the puzzle pieces are locked before the final square is placed. (We used this technique in the video).

2: Finish assembling the frame and add half of the tiles you have. Glue the tops of the tiles into place. Make sure to be centered as if the pieces aren't even, it may be wayside. But it does allows you to paint the frame.

Tip: If you are considering to paint the back of the tiles, make sure to sand it t'ill it's extremely smooth as one bit of rough paint could make it stick.

PRINT THE PARTS

I give you all the files , it's enough for a maker

Desing with my brain , and solidworks

THKS TO DIMAFIX/FLEXXION/AARON TUNELL

I will try to help you , it's not a tutorial , you have to be a little experimented in electronics

The three speed fan system works like this

The external electronics , must be disarmed by the switch , the system is now off , when the gcode will send a M126 command with value ' NOT ZERO' , the motherboard of the creator pro , not have pwm system , so it will just turn on or off the extra fan , so , when the extra speed fan is sent , the voltage will active permanently the ' DIMMER FAN SPEED' , it's a latch system , when the first ' extra speed command appears' , it turn on permanently the fan at the speed set in the dimmer
When the extra fan is on , the speed is full ' in the case of bridge of anything setted in your software '
Speed 1 : LAYER 1 FAN OFF for the first layer , wait the first extra fan gcode to start
Speed 2 : LAYER 2 FAN start with the first gcode '
Speed 3 : All layer that need extra fan speed , for bridge , when the extra fan is on , the dimmer is overlap by full power

To make this , you have to script your software to send the right command

First :
LAYER 1 EXTRA FAN = 0
LAYER 2 EXTRA FAN = 2
LAYER 3 EXTRA FAN = 0

Why the value '2' in layer 2, because , we will use a script ' in simplify3d ' to find where is ' layer 2' to activate the cooling , but , if you print object by object , we have many layer 2 to detect , to turn off the fan on their first layer , so i have find a good idea , i have set the fan value to ' 2' , that results a gcode like this ' M126 S5 ' , this gcode is unique and perfect to be found by my script , if i use value ' 1' , i'm afraid the script find all gcode M127 THAT STOP THE FAN , but with the '5' , the gcode is UNIQUE

second :
Don't use ' speed fan variation checked box ' in simplify
Third :
Put this script in simplify3d

{REPLACE "M126 S5" ";**\n;START FAN SCRIPT\n;**\nM126S255 \nM126S255 \nM126S255 \nM126S255 \nM126S255 \nM127"}

It seems not easy , but it's very easy , set the three layer fan speed like i said , put the script , disarm with the switch before start print and The miracle appears , your first layer fan is off , the second layer activates the dimmer , and when needed , you have extra fan that activates ' bridges and other '

ADDED: Mod Suggestion from @maestro72x If you find you'd like a larger particle size, print the new ring and slip onto the top piece of the grinder. 2xshells 1.2mm z height total.

Please respect the licence this is provided under.

https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0/ - Comply with this shit.... or I'll get all Woody Harrelsonon on yo' ass.

Apologies to the rest who are all awesome! On with it:

I've been meaning to design & print a working grinder that doesn't leave bits of plastic in the mix....

Saw a design that took from flour mill grinding plates, read the reviews, it sounds as though it needed another iteration / quality control check.

Improving upon the original, I've produced a similar design for you lovely, smokey printer fanatics - print in wood pla for a fantastic finish!
It literally pulverizes and obliterates evenly up to 2g of herb within three turns.

Please read the Print settings and see the image for assembly guidelines.

Shredder2.0 here: https://www.youmagine.com/designs/toothless-herb-grinder-shredder-2-0-by-420threed
Micro/Shred Here: https://www.youmagine.com/designs/micro-shred-by-420threed-toothless-herb-grinder

Duplicator i3

No

No

15

Notes:

For a complete gRINDER you will need to print:


1x Top Case

1x Bottom Case - Leaf OR Heart (the Heart is a TM of 420ThreeD)

OR 1xThicker Cases


1x Grinder



Print the Case's together on 2xshells 0%infill


Print the Grinder file separately: 3xshells 15%infil (min), top layers: 3

I cannot stress the 3x shells and 15% MIN infil enough, you don't want a holey print.

Although over 25% is EXCESSIVE and it just wastes filament / time / money.
15% is great
Happy Slicing!

Once you've got all the parts out,

Assemble the smaller grinder piece into the bottom, larger, case.
Then slide the larger grinder piece into the top, shorter, case.

Depending on the results from your printer you may need to glue the grinder pieces in to get a good turn.

Happy Grinding!

To assemble, I bought a piece of steel rod from the hardware store.

because the length of the rod varies between longshot, vulcan, and centurion. I ended up sticking the rod through, and eyeballing it.

description.text:
Updated; added; tyranid_devourer_center_hollow_tendrils.stl; this has tendril feelers on all appendages; includes a slight half-sphere hollow underneath.

Update; added mirrored tower

Update; 2x new towers/chimney added; it just fits the print bed on the Afinia... barely, you'll have to rotate along the z-axis. I believe I'll have to scale the one that is completely upright, it may be possible that I'll split that file so it can be printed large enough and in multiple pieces...

Updated: image and STL file; devourer_center was printed at 85% in size.

Work-in-Progress; CCW - Dune/Alien/Tyranid Terrain (lets mashup our sci-fi genres)
Can be used as capillary towers and spore chimney

Devourer_center should be reduced/scaled based on how large you want the mandible/towers. I might end up removing the talons mashed from the Ethereal Marauder and do something different... other files to follow as they get successfully printed.

Bases print hollowed; two reasons are to reduce filament and print time; however, you could also chuck in a 6 sided dice, shake it up and set it on the table. If one of the towers/mandibles is destroyed you lift it up and see what number is revealed and that is how many termagants are generated to come and defend the objective... anyone have any Megarachnids hanging around, lol.

Working on adding more shaping/detailing/muscle, tissue and pits/boils; possibly adding a "mouth" at the top of the spires/towers. Might also be usable as a basis for Tyrannocyte/Sporocyst model...

Not sure about scale/proportions but will play around with it; I currently use Heroscape Marro Hives and old Battle For Macragge bits, so those are starting reference points for scale.

The tower design is basically repeated/scaled/modular, so it's possibly to make them larger if they are truncated so you can fit it together from large base to smaller top...
